  "prompt": "Which are the best Hollywood movies of 2016?",
  "response": "2016 was a year with many notable and acclaimed Hollywood movies. Some of the best and highly regarded films from that year include:\n\n1. **La La Land** - Directed by Damien Chazelle, this musical romance stars Ryan Gosling and Emma Stone and received widespread critical acclaim, winning several Oscars including Best Director.\n\n2. **Moonlight** - Directed by Barry Jenkins, this film explores the life of a young African-American man grappling with his identity and sexuality. It won the Academy Award for Best Picture.\n\n3. **Manchester by the Sea** - Directed by Kenneth Lonergan, this drama stars Casey Affleck and Michelle Williams. Casey Affleck won an Oscar for Best Actor for his performance.\n\n4. **Arrival** - Directed by Denis Villeneuve, this science fiction film stars Amy Adams as a linguist trying to communicate with extraterrestrials. It was praised for its thought-provoking plot and strong performances.\n\n5. **Zootopia** - Directed by Byron Howard and Rich Moore, this animated film addresses themes of diversity and inclusion through a whimsical yet insightful narrative. It won the Oscar for Best Animated Feature.\n\n6. **Hell or High Water** - Directed by David Mackenzie, this modern Western crime drama stars Chris Pine and Ben Foster as brothers who resort to robbing banks to save their family ranch. Jeff Bridges also delivered a standout performance.\n\n7. **Hacksaw Ridge** - Directed by Mel Gibson, this war film tells the true story of Desmond Doss, a pacifist combat medic who served during World War II. It received several Oscar nominations and won two.\n\n8. **Captain America: Civil War** - Directed by Anthony and Joe Russo, this superhero film from the Marvel Cinematic Universe features an ensemble cast and exciting action sequences, receiving praise from both critics and audiences.\n\n9. **Rogue One: A Star Wars Story** - Directed by Gareth Edwards, this standalone Star Wars film was well-received for its gripping plot, visual effects, and connection to the broader Star Wars universe.\n\n10. **The Jungle Book** - Directed by Jon Favreau, this live-action/CGI adaptation of the classic tale was lauded for its visual effects and engaging storytelling.\n\nThese films were notable for their storytelling, performances, and impact, making them among the best Hollywood movies of 2016.",
